    },
    {
      "id": "0fad6f47_08c61768",
      "file_path": "onap-dcae-dcaepolicy-lib/tests/test_dcae_policy.py",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 152,
      "message": "You do not need to create a list from the keys (unless you modify the dict being iterated). the keys() function isn't needed either - dicts iterate over their keys normally.\nthus, both python2 and 3 work better with: for key in policy_body_1:",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 6172,
        "name": "Miroslav Los",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "miroslav.los@pantheon.tech",
        "username": "mirlos"
      },
      "updated": "2019-11-26 12:46:01.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "0ff70ad5_c61283dd",
      "file_path": "onap-dcae-dcaepolicy-lib/tests/test_dcae_policy.py",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 161,
      "message": "Let's assume val_1's __eq__ method doesn't always work with None, and you can't just write val_1 != val_2.\nThen, the proper formatting for this is :\nif (val_1 is None and val_2 is not None\n    or val_1 is not None and val_2 is None\n    or val_1 != val_2):\n\n    return False\n\nor, just after retrieving val_2 on line 157:\nif (val_1 is None) != (val_2 is None):\n    return False\n...\n<the recursive call>\n...\nif val_1 != val_2:\n   return False",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 6172,
        "name": "Miroslav Los",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "miroslav.los@pantheon.tech",
        "username": "mirlos"
      },
      "updated": "2019-11-26 12:46:01.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "75b18d18_89cc85e4",
      "file_path": "onap-dcae-dcaepolicy-lib/tests/test_dcae_policy.py",
      "patchset_number": 4,
      "line": 615,
      "message": "list(somedict) will return the list of its keys. Since it's using or, one could drop the {} and writte:\npolicy_filter_ids = list(runtime_properties.get(dcae_policy.POLICY_FILTERS) or [\"--\"])\n\nGiven that the same code is repeated many times below, perhaps one could have a function for this, and replace all occurences with a call to it.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 6172,
        "name": "Miroslav Los",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "miroslav.los@pantheon.tech",
        "username": "mirlos"
      },
      "updated": "2019-11-26 12:46:01.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
